# Fix UI Bug

When invoked, you receive a **spec file path** (e.g. `specs/eng-2042.md`). That file contains a bug title, a Linear issue URL, and a description of the expected vs. actual behavior. Your job is to understand the bug, implement a fix, verify it in the browser, clean up the branch, and open a PR — all without asking the user to do anything manually.

---

## Step 0: Parse the Spec

1. Read the spec file in full.
2. Extract:
   - **Ticket ID** — the `ENG-XXXX` string (case-insensitive). Normalize to lowercase for branch naming.
   - **Linear URL** — the `https://linear.app/...` link.
   - **Bug title** — the markdown heading.
   - **Description** — everything under `**Description**`.
3. Determine the current OS user for the branch prefix by running `whoami`.
4. Construct the **branch name**: `<whoami>-<ticket-id-lowercase>` (e.g. `lseper-eng-2042`).

---

## Step 1: Prepare the Branch

Run these commands sequentially in the `lens-www` directory:

```bash
git fetch origin main
git checkout -b <branch-name> origin/main
```

If the branch already exists locally, check it out and rebase onto `origin/main` instead:

```bash
git checkout <branch-name>
git rebase origin/main
```

---

## Step 2: Investigate the Bug

Launch **two parallel subagents** to build a full picture of the bug before writing any code.

### Subagent A — Codebase Investigation

> You are investigating a UI bug in a Next.js / React / TypeScript application.
>
> **Bug title:** <title>
> **Bug description:** <description>
> **Linear ticket:** <url>
>
> Your goal is to find the relevant source files, understand the current behavior, and identify the root cause. Do NOT make any changes.
>
> 1. Search the codebase for components, hooks, API routes, and state management related to the bug description. Use semantic search, grep, and glob to find all relevant files.
> 2. Read each relevant file thoroughly. Pay attention to:
>    - Component state and effects that control the described behavior
>    - Event handlers (onClick, onSubmit, onChange, etc.)
>    - API calls and their response handling
>    - Conditional rendering logic
>    - CSS classes that control visibility/layout relevant to the bug
> 3. Trace the data flow end-to-end: from user action → event handler → state change → re-render → visible outcome.
> 4. Identify the **root cause** — the specific line(s) or logic that produce the wrong behavior.
>
> Return a structured report:
> - **Relevant files** (with line ranges)
> - **Root cause** (specific code + explanation)
> - **Suggested fix** (what to change and why)
> - **Risk areas** (other components or flows that might be affected)

### Subagent B — Visual Baseline (agent-browser)

> You are capturing a visual baseline of the bug in the running application using agent-browser.
>
> **Bug title:** <title>
> **Bug description:** <description>
>
> Use `--session-name lens-www` for all agent-browser commands so the user's existing GitHub auth session is preserved.
>
> 1. Open the app at `http://localhost:3000` (or whatever port the dev server is running on — check the terminal).
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www open http://localhost:3000
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www wait --load networkidle
>    ```
> 2. If you are redirected to a login page, authenticate via GitHub OAuth:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www snapshot -i
>    ```
>    Look for a GitHub login/OAuth button and click it. The `lens-www` session should have stored credentials. If prompted for GitHub credentials, use the session's saved state. Wait for redirect back to the app.
> 3. Navigate to the area of the app described in the bug. Use snapshot + click to navigate through the UI.
> 4. **Reproduce the bug** — follow the steps implied by the description to trigger the incorrect behavior.
> 5. Take a **screenshot** of the buggy state:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www screenshot bug-baseline.png
>    ```
> 6. Take a **snapshot** of the accessibility tree in the buggy state to capture element structure.
>
> Return:
> - The navigation path you took (clicks, URLs)
> - The screenshot file path
> - The accessibility tree snapshot of the buggy area
> - Confirmation of whether the bug was reproduced, and what you observed

---

## Step 3: Implement the Fix

After both investigation subagents return, synthesize their findings and implement the fix.

1. **Plan the change** — Based on Subagent A's root cause analysis and Subagent B's visual confirmation, determine the minimal set of changes needed. Prefer the smallest diff that fully resolves the bug.
2. **Make the edits** — Edit the relevant files directly. Follow the project's existing patterns:
   - Use `cn()` from `clsx` for conditional classNames
   - No inline styles for visual state — use className toggles
   - No bare elements without classNames
   - CSS changes go in `workshop.css`
   - Follow the existing component/hook patterns in the file
3. **Lint check** — After editing, run lints on all changed files. Fix any lint errors you introduced.

---

## Step 4: Verify the Fix (agent-browser)

Launch a **browser-use subagent** to verify the fix in the running application.

> You are verifying that a UI bug has been fixed in the running application.
>
> **Bug title:** <title>
> **Bug description:** <description>
> **What was changed:** <summary of code changes>
> **Expected behavior after fix:** <expected behavior from the spec>
>
> Use `--session-name lens-www` for all agent-browser commands.
>
> **IMPORTANT:** Executions within this application can take upwards of multiple minutes to resolve. Be patient. When waiting for an execution or async operation, poll by re-snapshotting every 15-30 seconds to monitor progress. Do NOT give up after a single check.
>
> 1. The dev server should hot-reload with the changes. If not, wait a few seconds and refresh:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www open http://localhost:3000
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www wait --load networkidle
>    ```
> 2. If you need to log in, use the GitHub OAuth flow. The `lens-www` session should preserve auth. If redirected to login, snapshot, find the GitHub button, and click it.
> 3. Navigate to the area of the app where the bug was present (same path as the baseline).
> 4. **Verify the fix:**
>    - Confirm the described bug is no longer present.
>    - Confirm the expected behavior from the spec is now correct.
>    - Test edge cases: refresh the page, navigate away and back, try related workflows.
> 5. Take a **screenshot** of the fixed state:
>    ```bash
>    agent-browser --session-name lens-www screenshot bug-fixed.png
>    ```
> 6. If the bug is **NOT fixed**, return a detailed report of what you still observe, including snapshots and screenshots.
> 7. If the bug **IS fixed**, confirm success with evidence (screenshot path, snapshot diff, observed behavior).
>
> Return:
> - **Status:** FIXED or NOT_FIXED
> - **Evidence:** screenshot path, what you observed
> - **Edge cases tested** and results
> - If NOT_FIXED: detailed description of remaining issue

### If verification fails (NOT_FIXED):

1. Re-read the subagent's report carefully.
2. Re-examine the code changes and the root cause analysis.
3. Make corrective edits.
4. Re-launch the verification subagent (repeat Step 4).
5. Iterate up to **3 times**. If the bug persists after 3 attempts, stop and report to the user with all evidence collected.

---

## Step 5: Commit the Fix

Once verification passes:

```bash
git add -A
git commit -m "<ticket-id>: <concise description of the fix>"
```

Use the ticket ID as the commit message prefix (e.g. `ENG-2042: hide floating controls until first edit`).

---

## Step 6: Clean the Branch

Delegate to the **clean** rule (`.cursor/rules/clean.mdc`).

Invoke the clean rule against the current branch. It will review all changed files compared to `main` for structural and engineering quality issues and fix them without altering functionality. After it completes, review its summary and commit any cleanup changes:

```bash
git add -A
git commit -m "<ticket-id>: clean up structural issues"
```

If clean reports no issues, skip this commit.

---

## Step 7: Open the PR

Delegate to the **make-lens-pr** rule (`.cursor/rules/make-lens-pr.mdc`).

Invoke the PR rule with:
- **Source branch:** `<branch-name>`
- **Destination branch:** `main`

The PR title should be the bug title from the spec. The description should reference the Linear ticket URL and summarize the fix.

---

## Summary of Execution Order

```
Step 0: Parse spec → extract ticket, description, branch name
Step 1: Create/checkout feature branch off main
Step 2: [PARALLEL] Investigate codebase (Subagent A) + Capture visual baseline (Subagent B)
Step 3: Implement the fix
Step 4: Verify fix in browser (loop up to 3x if failing)
Step 5: Commit the fix
Step 6: Delegate → clean rule
Step 7: Delegate → make-lens-pr rule
```
